Here I investigate how Salt Lake City's air quality has changed over time through the use of these libraries: 
 - requests:
 - zipfile:
 - io:
 - glob:
 - pandas:
 - matplotlib:

As a child, I remember watching my dad clean the fish tank. This was a bit of a monthly ritual, as over that length of time it would go from clear to cloudy to “we should not be pet owners” dirty. I always felt bad for the fish in the days preceding this cleaning – when they were clearly bopping around in some nasty stuff.

<center>

<img src="{{ site.url }}{{ site.baseurl }}/assets/images/SLC_Air_Quality/dirty_tank.jpg " alt="dirty fish tank">

</center>

<p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;"> Not the fish tank of my childhood, but similar. </p>

Household fish aren’t the only ones subjected to such conditions, many of us live in areas with dirty air. Here’s a map of PM2.5 pollution (small particles that irritate lungs) in the US:

<center>

<img src="{{ site.url }}{{ site.baseurl }}/assets/images/SLC_Air_Quality/us_air.jpg " alt="U.S. map of PM2.5 air pollution">

</center>

<p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;"> PM2.5 air pollution across the U.S. </p>

The blotch of red towards the middle-left of the country is Salt Lake City, where due to the perimeter of mountains surrounding the inhabited valley floor (forming a bowl-like geometry), nasty air can get trapped and accumulate. This is especially bad in the winter, when a blanket of warm air forms a “lid” so-to-speak on top of the colder valley floor – this effect is called the winter inversion, which is a spooky name.

I had heard about this prior to moving to SLC. Second to skiing it seemed to be the main thing non-Utahns knew about the area. But this winter I really haven’t seen a cause for concern. Admittedly, I don’t check air quality often, but if it was really that bad I think I’d have heard? That all said, I was curious to see what the air quality in SLC is today and how it has changed over time.

I came across an article in DeseretNews titled “Visualizing SLC air pollution in 35 years and what it tells us.” The article, which you can view [here]( https://www.deseret.com/2015/5/7/20564270/visualizing-slc-air-pollution-in-35-years-and-what-it-tells-us), links to a web-based visualization which unfortunately returns “site can’t be reached.” I sent the article’s author a note to let her know, and in the meantime decided to see if I could pull air quality data and visualize it myself.

The EPA makes air quality data readily available to the public via their AirData Quality Monitors web app. Below are all the monitors across the U.S. for the 5 primary pollutants used in evaluating air quality (carbon monoxide, nitrogen dioxide, ozone, PM2.5, and sulfur dioxide):

<center>

<img src="{{ site.url }}{{ site.baseurl }}/assets/images/SLC_Air_Quality/US_monitors.png" alt="EPA air quality monitors in the U.S.">

</center>

<p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;"> Air quality monitors in the U.S. </p>

Zooming in on SLC, you can see the valley has 5 monitors:

<center>

<img src="{{ site.url }}{{ site.baseurl }}/assets/images/SLC_Air_Quality/valley_monitors.png" alt="Air quality monitors in Salt Lake City">

</center>

<p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;"> Air quality monitors in Salt Lake City. </p>

The EPA uses data from these monitors to calculate an Air Quality Index (known as AQI), which has six categories:

<center>

<img src="{{ site.url }}{{ site.baseurl }}/assets/images/SLC_Air_Quality/AQI_table.png" alt="AQI table: 0-50=good, 51-100=moderate,101-150=unhealthy for sensitive groups, 151-200=unhealthy, 210-300=very unhealthy, hazardous=301-500">

</center>

<p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;"> The Air Quality Index (AQI) categories. </p>

From the EPA:
"EPA calculates the AQI for five major air pollutants regulated by the Clean Air Act:

- ground-level ozone
- particle pollution (also known as particulate matter)
- carbon monoxide
- sulfur dioxide
- nitrogen dioxide

For each of these pollutants, EPA has established national air quality standards to protect public health .Ground-level ozone and airborne particles are the two pollutants that pose the greatest threat to human health in this country."

The EPA has made daily AQI data across the U.S. available for 1980 to today. 2019's data isn't complete just yet, so I pulled data for 1980 to 2018:


```python
import pandas as pd
import requests
import zipfile
import glob
import io


#might not need these for the intitial work:
# import json
# from pandas.io.json import json_normalize

#pulling annual AQI data by county for 1980 to 2018, unzipping and placing the csv files in a folder on my desktop
for i in range(1980, 2019):
    zip_file_url = 'https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/airdata/annual_aqi_by_county_' + str(i) + '.zip'
    r = requests.get(zip_file_url, stream=True)
    z = zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(r.content))
    z.extractall(r'C:\Users\Pat\Desktop\zip_files')


#combining all csv files into one dataframe, ignoring column headers after the first file
path = r'C:\Users\Pat\Desktop\zip_files'
all_files = glob.glob(path + "/*.csv")

li = []

for filename in all_files:
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, index_col=None, header=0)
    li.append(df)

all_counties_df = pd.concat(li, axis=0, ignore_index=True)


#filtering the datafrarme for Salt Lake county only
df_SLC = all_counties_df[all_counties_df.County == 'Salt Lake']

df_SLC.head(5)
```

print(json_data)

     <h1 class="page-title">Pre-Generated Data Files</h1>
     <div class="panel-pane pane-node-content">
     <div class="pane-content">
     <div class="node node-page clearfix view-mode-full">
     <!-- C O N T E N T    B L O C K    B E G I N  -->
     <p id="main-content">This page contains pre-generated files of data available for download.  The files are updated twice per year: once in June to capture the complete data for the prior year and once in December to capture the data for the summer (ozone season).</p>
     <p>
     <a href="#Meta">Site and Monitor Descriptions</a><br/>
     <a href="#Annual">Table of Annual Summary Data</a><br/>
     <a href="#Daily">Tables of Daily and Daily Summary Data</a><br/>
     <a href="#AQI">Tables of Daily AQI</a><br/>
     <a href="#Raw">Tables of Hourly Data</a><br/>
     <a href="#eighthour">Tables of 8-Hour Average Data</a><br/>
     <a href="#Blanks">Table of Blanks Data</a></p>
     <br/>
     <h3>About the data</h3>
     <p><a href="FileFormats.html">Description of data and formats</a></p>
     <p>This page contains large files of data intended for use by people who
     	understand the EPA ambient air quality monitoring program and data.
     	<a href="https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data/air-data-basic-information#other">Other sources of data</a> are available.</p>
     <p>The data available here is also available via<a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/data_api.html">
         an API.</a></p>
     <p>Some contain data summarized on an annual basis (annual summary files),
         some contain data summarized on a daily basis (daily summary), and
         some contain raw data (sample data as reported).
         These are the standard time aggregations EPA calculates and stores
         (we do not have monthly data).  All but the annual summary have
         data files grouped by parameter:</p>
     <ul>
     <li>Criteria Gases</li>
     <li>Particulates</li>
     <li>Meteorological</li>
     <li>Toxics (see "Notes on Toxics" below), Ozone Precursors, and Lead</li>
     <li>Blanks (Blanks are empty cannisters that are measured for speciation quality assurance reasons)</li>
     </ul>
     <p>The annual summary files are small enough to include all data in one file.</p>
     <p>Each group has data listed by year, in reverse order, back to 1990.</p>
     <p>Each table entry has the file name, linked to the file,
         the size of the (zipped) file, the number of data rows in the file,
         and the date the file was last modified.  EPA will update these files
         twice per year; in the spring and fall (late May and November).  Keep in
         mind, data collection agencies have up to 6 months to report their data.
         <p>The files are all comma separated text with a header.  Each aggregate level
         has a different format.</p>
     <p><em>Notes on Toxics</em>.</p>
     <p>1. While this page contains information on toxics, it is suggested you get
     	toxics data from the <a href="https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/amtic/toxdat.html#data">EPA toxics archive</a>.  
     	It is a value added product that includes additional data quality assurance and reduction.
     	The toxics data is included on this page for those needed it in a consistent
     	format with other AQS data.</p>
     <p>2. EPA has several ways of grouping parameters.
         For the parameters listed here as toxics we have included two groups
         of parameters: Core HAPS (Hazardous Air Pollutants) and VOCs ( Volatile
         Organic Compounds).  The VOC list was expanded with the December 2015
         update.  These lists include the parameters as defined in
         the EPA AQS system as "CORE HAPS" or "VOC".  You can view the list
         of parameters included in either catagory by visiting the
         <a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/codetables/parameter_classes.html">
         AQS Code Tables page for Parameter Classes</a> and searching for CORE_HAPS or VOC.</p>
     <p>The Air Quality Index (AQI) values are presented in several files.
         AQI is calculated each day for each monitor for the Criteria
         Gases and PM10 and PM2.5 (FRM and non FRM).  The AQI values are on the
         respective records in those Daily Summary files.  There are also annual
         summary AQI files that show by CBSA (metro area) or county the annual
         statistics for AQI (max, number of values in each category, etc.).
         This file has one record per year per CBSA or county.
         There are also daily summary files that show the AQI by CBSA or county.
         These have one record per day per CBSA or county.</p>
     <p>For reference, there is also a <a href="file_list.csv">file</a>
         listing all of the files on this page and the date they were modified.
         Each file also includes the last change date of each record in the file.
         	<br/><hr/><br/>

href="https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data">Air Data Home</a>\n\n      <h1 class="page-title">Pre-Generated Data Files</h1>\n      <div class="panel-pane pane-node-content" >\n        <div class="pane-content">\n          <div class="node node-page clearfix view-mode-full">\n\n\n\n      <!-- C O N T E N T    B L O C K    B E G I N  -->\n    \n\n\n\n\n    <P ID="main-content">This page contains pre-generated files of data available for download.  The files are updated twice per year: once in June to capture the complete data for the prior year and once in December to capture the data for the summer (ozone season).</P>\n    <p>\n    <a href="#Meta">Site and Monitor Descriptions</a><br>\n    <a href="#Annual">Table of Annual Summary Data</a><br>\n    <a href="#Daily">Tables of Daily and Daily Summary Data</a><br>\n    <a href="#AQI">Tables of Daily AQI</a><br>\n    <a href="#Raw">Tables of Hourly Data</a><br>\n    <a href="#eighthour">Tables of 8-Hour Average Data</a><br>\n    <a href="#Blanks">Table of Blanks Data</a></p>\n    <BR>\n    <H3>About the data</H3>\n    <p><a href="FileFormats.html">Description of data and formats</a></p>\n\t<p>This page contains large files of data intended for use by people who \n\tunderstand the EPA ambient air quality monitoring program and data. \n\t<a href="https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data/air-data-basic-information#other">Other sources of data</a> are available.</p>\n    <p>The data available here is also available via<a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/data_api.html">\n    an API.</a></p>\n\n    <P>Some contain data summarized on an annual basis (annual summary files),\n    some contain data summarized on a daily basis (daily summary), and\n    some contain raw data (sample data as reported).\n    These are the standard time aggregations EPA calculates and stores\n    (we do not have monthly data).  All but the annual summary have \n    data files grouped by parameter:</P>\n    <UL>\n    <LI>Criteria Gases</LI>\n    <LI>Particulates</LI>\n    <LI>Meteorological</LI>\n    <LI>Toxics (see "Notes on Toxics" below), Ozone Precursors, and Lead</LI>\n    <LI>Blanks (Blanks are empty cannisters that are measured for speciation quality assurance reasons)</LI>\n    </UL>\n    <P>The annual summary files are small enough to include all data in one file.</P>\n    <P>Each group has data listed by year, in reverse order, back to 1990.</P>\n    <P>Each table entry has the file name, linked to the file,\n    the size of the (zipped) file, the number of data rows in the file,\n    and the date the file was last modified.  EPA will update these files\n    twice per year; in the spring and fall (late May and November).  Keep in\n    mind, data collection agencies have up to 6 months to report their data.\n    <P>The files are all comma separated text with a header.  Each aggregate level\n    has a different format.</P>\n    <P><em>Notes on Toxics</em>.</p>\n\t<p>1. While this page contains information on toxics, it is suggested you get\n\ttoxics data from the <a href="https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/amtic/toxdat.html#data">EPA toxics archive</a>.  \n\tIt is a value added product that includes additional data quality assurance and reduction.\n\tThe toxics data is included on this page for those needed it in a consistent\n\tformat with other AQS data.</p>\n    <p>2. EPA has several ways of grouping parameters.\n    For the parameters listed here as toxics we have included two groups\n    of parameters: Core HAPS (Hazardous Air Pollutants) and VOCs ( Volatile\n    Organic Compounds).  The VOC list was expanded with the December 2015\n    update.  These lists include the parameters as defined in\n    the EPA AQS system as "CORE HAPS" or "VOC".  You can view the list\n    of parameters included in either catagory by visiting the \n    <a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/codetables/parameter_classes.html">\n    AQS Code Tables page for Parameter Classes</a> and searching for CORE_HAPS or VOC.</p>\n\t\n    <P>The Air Quality Index (AQI) values are presented in several files.\n    AQI is calculated each day for each monitor for the Criteria\n    Gases and PM10 and PM2.5 (FRM and non FRM).  The AQI values are on the\n    respective records in those Daily Summary files.  There are also annual\n    summary AQI files that show by CBSA (metro area) or county the annual\n    statistics for AQI (max, number of values in each category, etc.).\n    This file has one record per year per CBSA or county.\n    There are also daily summary files that show the AQI by CBSA or county.\n    These have one record per day per CBSA or county.</P>\n    <P>For reference, there is also a <a href="file_list.csv">file</a>\n    listing all of the files on this page and the date they were modified.\n    Each file also includes the last change date of each record in the file.\n    \t<BR><HR><BR>\n\t<H2 ID="Meta">Site and Monitor Descriptions</H2>\n\t<a href="aqs_sites.zip">Site Listing</a> (20,611 Rows, 982 KB)<BR>\n\t<a href="aqs_monitors.zip">Monitor Listing</a> (353,283              <p id="main-content">
              This page contains pre-generated files of data available for download.  The files are updated twice per year: once in June to capture the complete data for the prior year and once in December to capture the data for the summer (ozone season).
             </p>
             <p>
              <a href="#Meta">
               Site and Monitor Descriptions
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#Annual">
               Table of Annual Summary Data
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#Daily">
               Tables of Daily and Daily Summary Data
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#AQI">
               Tables of Daily AQI
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#Raw">
               Tables of Hourly Data
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#eighthour">
               Tables of 8-Hour Average Data
              </a>
              <br/>
              <a href="#Blanks">
               Table of Blanks Data
              </a>
             </p>
             <br/>
             <h3>
              About the data
             </h3>
             <p>
              <a href="FileFormats.html">
               Description of data and formats
              </a>
             </p>
             <p>
              This page contains large files of data intended for use by people who
    	understand the EPA ambient air quality monitoring program and data.
              <a href="https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data/air-data-basic-information#other">
               Other sources of data
              </a>
              are available.
             </p>
             <p>
              The data available here is also available via
              <a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/data_api.html">
               an API.
              </a>
             </p>
             <p>
              Some contain data summarized on an annual basis (annual summary files),
        some contain data summarized on a daily basis (daily summary), and
        some contain raw data (sample data as reported).
        These are the standard time aggregations EPA calculates and stores
        (we do not have monthly data).  All but the annual summary have
        data files grouped by parameter:
             </p>
             <ul>
              <li>
               Criteria Gases
              </li>
              <li>
               Particulates
              </li>
              <li>
               Meteorological
              </li>
              <li>
               Toxics (see "Notes on Toxics" below), Ozone Precursors, and Lead
              </li>
              <li>
               Blanks (Blanks are empty cannisters that are measured for speciation quality assurance reasons)
              </li>
             </ul>
             <p>
              The annual summary files are small enough to include all data in one file.
             </p>
             <p>
              Each group has data listed by year, in reverse order, back to 1990.
             </p>
             <p>
              Each table entry has the file name, linked to the file,
        the size of the (zipped) file, the number of data rows in the file,
        and the date the file was last modified.  EPA will update these files
        twice per year; in the spring and fall (late May and November).  Keep in
        mind, data collection agencies have up to 6 months to report their data.
              <p>
               The files are all comma separated text with a header.  Each aggregate level
        has a different format.
              </p>
              <p>
               <em>
                Notes on Toxics
               </em>
               .
              </p>
              <p>
               1. While this page contains information on toxics, it is suggested you get
    	toxics data from the
               <a href="https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/amtic/toxdat.html#data">
                EPA toxics archive
               </a>
               .  
    	It is a value added product that includes additional data quality assurance and reduction.
    	The toxics data is included on this page for those needed it in a consistent
    	format with other AQS data.
              </p>
              <p>
               2. EPA has several ways of grouping parameters.
        For the parameters listed here as toxics we have included two groups
        of parameters: Core HAPS (Hazardous Air Pollutants) and VOCs ( Volatile
        Organic Compounds).  The VOC list was expanded with the December 2015
        update.  These lists include the parameters as defined in
        the EPA AQS system as "CORE HAPS" or "VOC".  You can view the list
        of parameters included in either catagory by visiting the
               <a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/codetables/parameter_classes.html">
                AQS Code Tables page for Parameter Classes
               </a>
               and searching for CORE_HAPS or VOC.
              </p>
              <p>
               The Air Quality Index (AQI) values are presented in several files.
        AQI is calculated each day for each monitor for the Criteria
        Gases and PM10 and PM2.5 (FRM and non FRM).  The AQI values are on the
        respective records in those Daily Summary files.  There are also annual
        summary AQI files that show by CBSA (metro area) or county the annual
        statistics for AQI (max, number of values in each category, etc.).
        This file has one record per year per CBSA or county.
        There are also daily summary files that show the AQI by CBSA or county.
        These have one record per day per CBSA or county.
              </p>
              <p>
               For reference, there is also a
               <a href="file_list.csv">
                file
               </a>
               listing all of the files on this page and the date they were modified.
        Each file also includes the last change date of each record in the file.

     <p id="main-content">This page contains pre-generated files of data available for download.  The files are updated twice per year: once in June to capture the complete data for the prior year and once in December to capture the data for the summer (ozone season).</p>

     <h3>About the data</h3>
     <p><a href="FileFormats.html">Description of data and formats</a></p>
     <p>This page contains large files of data intended for use by people who
     	understand the EPA ambient air quality monitoring program and data.
     	<a href="https://www.epa.gov/outdoor-air-quality-data/air-data-basic-information#other">Other sources of data</a> are available.</p>
     <p>The data available here is also available via<a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/data_api.html">
         an API.</a></p>
     <p>Some contain data summarized on an annual basis (annual summary files),
         some contain data summarized on a daily basis (daily summary), and
         some contain raw data (sample data as reported).
         These are the standard time aggregations EPA calculates and stores
         (we do not have monthly data).  All but the annual summary have
         data files grouped by parameter:</p>
     <ul>
     <li>Criteria Gases</li>
     <li>Particulates</li>
     <li>Meteorological</li>
     <li>Toxics (see "Notes on Toxics" below), Ozone Precursors, and Lead</li>
     <li>Blanks (Blanks are empty cannisters that are measured for speciation quality assurance reasons)</li>
     </ul>
     <p>The annual summary files are small enough to include all data in one file.</p>
     <p>Each group has data listed by year, in reverse order, back to 1990.</p>
     <p>Each table entry has the file name, linked to the file,
         the size of the (zipped) file, the number of data rows in the file,
         and the date the file was last modified.  EPA will update these files
         twice per year; in the spring and fall (late May and November).  Keep in
         mind, data collection agencies have up to 6 months to report their data.
         <p>The files are all comma separated text with a header.  Each aggregate level
         has a different format.</p>
     <p><em>Notes on Toxics</em>.</p>
     <p>1. While this page contains information on toxics, it is suggested you get
     	toxics data from the <a href="https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/amtic/toxdat.html#data">EPA toxics archive</a>.  
     	It is a value added product that includes additional data quality assurance and reduction.
     	The toxics data is included on this page for those needed it in a consistent
     	format with other AQS data.</p>
     <p>2. EPA has several ways of grouping parameters.
         For the parameters listed here as toxics we have included two groups
         of parameters: Core HAPS (Hazardous Air Pollutants) and VOCs ( Volatile
         Organic Compounds).  The VOC list was expanded with the December 2015
         update.  These lists include the parameters as defined in
         the EPA AQS system as "CORE HAPS" or "VOC".  You can view the list
         of parameters included in either catagory by visiting the
         <a href="https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/codetables/parameter_classes.html">
         AQS Code Tables page for Parameter Classes</a> and searching for CORE_HAPS or VOC.</p>
     <p>The Air Quality Index (AQI) values are presented in several files.
         AQI is calculated each day for each monitor for the Criteria
         Gases and PM10 and PM2.5 (FRM and non FRM).  The AQI values are on the
         respective records in those Daily Summary files.  There are also annual
         summary AQI files that show by CBSA (metro area) or county the annual
         statistics for AQI (max, number of values in each category, etc.).
         This file has one record per year per CBSA or county.
         There are also daily summary files that show the AQI by CBSA or county.
         These have one record per day per CBSA or county.</p>
     <p>For reference, there is also a <a href="file_list.csv">file</a>
         listing all of the files on this page and the date they were modified.
         Each file also includes the last change date of each record in the file.
         	<br/><hr/><br/>
